ough the end of the war. At the same time, it gives an unsparing account of the xenophobia and bureaucratic infighting that nearly prevented their rescue—and that helped to seal the fate of countless other European Jews for whom escape was never an option. From the introduction: This book is called Nearly the New World because for most refugees who found sanctuary, it was nearly, but not quite, the New World that they had hoped for. The British West Indies were a way station, a temporary destination that allowed them entry when the United States, much of South and Central America, the United Kingdom and Palestine had all become closed. For a small number, it became their home. This is the first comprehensive study of modern Jewish emigration to the British West Indies. It reveals how the histories of the Caribbean, of refugees, and of the Holocaust connect through the potential and actual involvement of the British West Indies as a refuge during the 1930s and the Second World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aImmigrantszWest Indies, BritishxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewish refugeeszWest Indies, BritishxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszWest Indies, BritishxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewszWest Indies, British. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  a1930s.  aJewish immigration.  abarbados.  aeuropean jews.  ahitler.  aholocaust.  aimmigrant stories.  ajamaica.  ajewish history.  ajewish refugees.  amemoirs.  anazi germany.  anazis.  apersecution.  areligious freedom.  atrinidad.  awest indies.  aww ii history.  axenophobia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311099772940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781789203349?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781789203349423Coveruhttps://www.